{"title_page": "Psychodynamic psychotherapy", "text_new": "{{Psychology sidebar}}\n{{Infobox interventions | MeshYear = 2014 | ICD10 = | ICD9 = | MeshID = D064889 | OPS301 = | OtherCodes = | = }}\n'''Psychodynamic psychotherapy''' or '''psychoanalytic psychotherapy'''<ref>British Psychoanalytic Council. (2018). [https://www.bpc.org.uk/about-psychotherapy/what-psychotherapy What is psychoanalytic psychotherapy?]</ref><ref>American Psychoanalytical Association (2018). [http://www.apsa.org/content/psychoanalytic-psychotherapy Psychoanalytic Psychotherapy]</ref> is a form of [[depth psychology]], the primary focus of which is to reveal the unconscious content of a client's psyche in an effort to alleviate psychic tension.<ref>[http://www.guidetopsychology.com/txtypes.htm#Psychodynamic Psychodynamic psychotherapy] - guidetopsychology.com</ref>\n\nPsychodynamic psychotherapy relies on the interpersonal relationship between client and therapist more than other forms of depth psychology. In terms of approach, this form of therapy uses psychoanalysis adapted to a less intensive style of working, usually at a frequency of once or twice per week. Principal theorists drawn upon are Freud, Klein, and theorists of the [[object relations theory|object relations movement]], e.g., Winnicott, Guntrip, and Bion. Some psychodynamic therapists also draw on [[Carl Jung|Jung]] or [[Jacques Lacan|Lacan]]. It is a focus that has been used in [[individual psychotherapy]], [[group psychotherapy]], [[family therapy]], and to understand and work with institutional and organizational contexts.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Granstr\u00f6m|first1=Kjell|title=Dynamik i arbetsgrupper|date=2006|publisher=[[Studentlitteratur]] |location=Lund|isbn=9789144008523|pages=197|edition=2}}</ref> In [[psychiatry]], it is considered a treatment of choice for [[adjustment disorders]], as well as [[posttraumatic stress disorder]] (PTSD) but more for personality-related disorders.<ref name=\"AgroninMaletta2006\">{{cite book|last1=Agronin|first1=Marc E.|last2=Maletta|first2=Gabe J.|title=Principles and Practice of Geriatric Psychiatry|year=2006|publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|language=English |isbn=9780781748100|page=423}}</ref><ref name=\"Corales2005\">{{cite book|last=Corales|first=Thomas A.|title=Trends in Posttraumatic Stress Disorder Research|year=2005|publisher=Nova Publishers|language=English |isbn=9781594541353|page=6}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe principles of [[psychodynamics]] were introduced in the 1874 publication ''Lectures on Physiology'' by German scientist [[Ernst Wilhelm von Br\u00fccke]]. Von Br\u00fccke, taking a cue from [[thermodynamics]], suggested all living organisms are energy systems, governed by the principle of [[Conservation of energy|energy conservation]]. During the same year, von Br\u00fccke was supervisor to first-year medical student [[Sigmund Freud]] at the [[University of Vienna]]. Freud later adopted this new construct of \u201cdynamic\u201d physiology to aid in his own conceptualization of the human psyche. Later, both the concept and application of psychodynamics were further developed by the likes of [[Carl Jung]], [[Alfred Adler]], [[Otto Rank]], and [[Melanie Klein]].<ref>[[Horacio Etchegoyen]]: ''The Fundamentals of Psychoanalytic Technique'', Karnac Books ed., New Ed, 2005, {{ISBN|1-85575-455-X}}{{page needed|date=December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Approaches==\n{{More citations needed section|date=April 2017}}\nMost psychodynamic approaches are centered on the concept that some maladaptive functioning is in play, and that this maladaption is, at least in part, [[Unconscious mind|unconscious]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Horowitz|first=Mardi J.|title=Introduction to psychodynamics: A new synthesis|publisher=Basic Books|year=1988}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1002/(sici)1097-4679(200006)56:6<723::aid-jclp3>3.0.co;2-3|title=Attributional style and defense mechanisms: A synthesis of cognitive and psychodynamic factors in depression|journal=Journal of Clinical Psychology|volume=56|issue=6|pages=723\u2013735|year=2000|last1=Kwon|first1=Paul|last2=Lemon|first2=Katherine E.}}</ref> The presumed maladaption develops early in life<ref>Lerner, H. \"Psychodynamic perspectives.\" The Handbook of Clinical Psychology 1 (2008): 127-160.</ref> and eventually causes difficulties in day-to-day life. Psychodynamic therapies focus on revealing and resolving these unconscious conflicts that are driving their symptoms.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1016/0272-7358(85)90047-9|title=Research on psychoanalytic psychodynamic propositions|journal=Clinical Psychology Review|volume=5|issue=3|pages=247\u2013257|year=1985|last1=Silverman|first1=Lloyd H.}}</ref> Major techniques used by psychodynamic therapists include [[Free association (psychology)|free association]], [[Interpretation of Dreams|dream interpretation]], recognizing resistance and [[transference]], working through painful memories and difficult issues, and building a strong therapeutic alliance. As in some psychoanalytic approaches, the therapeutic relationship is seen as a key means to understanding and working through the relational difficulties which the client has suffered in life.\n\n==Core principles and characteristics==\nAlthough psychodynamic psychotherapy can take many forms, commonalities include:<ref>{{cite book |last=Sundberg |first=Norman |title=Clinical Psychology: Evolving Theory, Practice, and Research |publisher=Prentice Hall |location=Englewood Cliffs |year=2001 |isbn=978-0-13-087119-0 }}{{page needed|date=December 2014}}</ref>\n* An emphasis on the centrality of intrapsychic and unconscious conflicts, and their relation to development\n* Identifying defenses as developing in internal psychic structures in order to avoid unpleasant consequences of conflict\n* A belief that psychopathology develops especially from early childhood experiences\n* A view that internal representations of experiences are organized around interpersonal relations\n* A conviction that life issues and dynamics will re-emerge in the context of the client-therapist relationship as [[transference]] and [[counter-transference]]\n* Use of [[Free association (psychology)|free association]] as a major method for exploration of internal conflicts and problems\n* Focusing on interpretations of [[transference]], defense mechanisms, and current symptoms and the [[working through]] of these present problems\n* Trust in [[insight]] as critically important for success in therapy\n\n==Efficacy==\nPsychodynamic psychotherapy, both short-term and long-term, is an effective psychotherapy. Psychodynamic psychotherapy is an evidence-based therapy (Schedler 2010) and its more intensive form, psychoanalysis has been proven to be evidence-based, also. Later meta-analyses showed psychoanalysis and psychodynamic therapy to be effective, with outcomes comparable or greater than other kinds of [[psychotherapy]] or [[antidepressant drugs]],<ref>{{cite journal |author=Shedler J |title=The efficacy of psychodynamic psychotherapy |journal=The American Psychologist |volume=65 |issue=2 |pages=98\u2013109 |year=2010 |pmid=20141265 |doi=10.1037/a0018378|citeseerx=10.1.1.607.2980 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Leichsenring F |title=Are psychodynamic and psychoanalytic therapies effective?: A review of empirical data |journal=The International Journal of Psycho-Analysis |volume=86 |issue=Pt 3 |pages=841\u201368 |date=June 2005  |pmid=16096078 |doi=10.1516/rfee-lkpn-b7tf-kpdu}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid21719877\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Leichsenring F, Rabung S |title=Long-term psychodynamic psychotherapy in complex mental disorders: update of a meta-analysis |journal=The British Journal of Psychiatry |volume=199 |issue=1 |pages=15\u201322 |date=July 2011  |pmid=21719877 |doi=10.1192/bjp.bp.110.082776}}</ref> but these arguments have also been subjected to various criticisms.<ref>{{cite journal |author=McKay D |title=Methods and mechanisms in the efficacy of psychodynamic psychotherapy |journal=The American Psychologist |volume=66 |issue=2 |pages=147\u20138; discussion 152\u20134 |year=2011 |pmid=21299262 |doi=10.1037/a0021195|url=https://fordham.bepress.com/psych_facultypubs/318 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Thombs BD, Jewett LR, Bassel M |title=Is there room for criticism of studies of psychodynamic psychotherapy? |journal=The American Psychologist |volume=66 |issue=2 |pages=148\u20139; discussion 152\u20134 |year=2011 |pmid=21299263 |doi=10.1037/a0021248}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Anestis MD, Anestis JC, Lilienfeld SO |title=When it comes to evaluating psychodynamic therapy, the devil is in the details |journal=The American Psychologist |volume=66 |issue=2 |pages=149\u201351; discussion 152\u20134 |year=2011 |pmid=21299264 |doi=10.1037/a0021190}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Tryon WW, Tryon GS |title=No ownership of common factors |journal=The American Psychologist |volume=66 |issue=2 |pages=151\u20132; discussion 152\u20134 |year=2011 |pmid=21299265 |doi=10.1037/a0021056}}</ref> For example, [[Meta-analyses]] in 2012 and 2013 came to the conclusion that there is little support or evidence for the efficacy of psychoanalytic therapy, thus further research is needed<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Leichsenring F, Abbass A, Luyten P, Hilsenroth M, Rabung S |title=The emerging evidence for long-term psychodynamic therapy |journal=Psychodynamic Psychiatry |volume=41 |issue=3 |pages=361\u201384 |year=2013 |pmid=24001160 |doi=10.1521/pdps.2013.41.3.361}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal  |vauthors=de Maat S, de Jonghe F, de Kraker R, etal |title=The current state of the empirical evidence for psychoanalysis: a meta-analytic approach |journal=Harvard Review of Psychiatry |volume=21 |issue=3 |pages=107\u201337 |year=2013 |pmid=23660968 |doi=10.1097/HRP.0b013e318294f5fd|doi-broken-date=2019-12-11 |url=https://journals.lww.com/hrpjournal/fulltext/2013/05000/The_Current_State_of_the_Empirical_Evidence_for.1.aspx}}</ref>.\n\nA system review of Long Term Psychodynamic Psychotherapy (LTPP) in 2009 found an overall effect size of .33.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Smit Y, Huibers MJ, Ioannidis JP, van Dyck R, van Tilburg W, Arntz A |title=The effectiveness of long-term psychoanalytic psychotherapy--a meta-analysis of randomized controlled trials |journal=Clinical Psychology Review |volume=32 |issue=2 |pages=81\u201392 |date=March 2012  |pmid=22227111 |doi=10.1016/j.cpr.2011.11.003}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> Others have found effect sizes of .44\u2013.68.<ref name=\"pmid21719877\" />\n\nMeta-analyses of Short Term Psychodynamic Psychotherapy (STPP) have found effect sizes ranging from .34\u2013.71 compared to no treatment and was found to be slightly better than other therapies in follow up.<ref>{{cite journal |first1=Edward M. |last1=Anderson |first2=Michael J. |last2=Lambert |title=Short-term dynamically oriented psychotherapy: A review and meta-analysis |journal=Clinical Psychology Review |volume=15 |issue=6 |year=1995 |pages=503\u201314 |doi=10.1016/0272-7358(95)00027-M}}</ref> Other reviews have found an effect size of .78\u2013.91 for [[Somatoform disorder|somatic disorders]] compared to no treatment<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Abbass A, Kisely S, Kroenke K |title=Short-term psychodynamic psychotherapy for somatic disorders. Systematic review and meta-analysis of clinical trials |journal=Psychotherapy and Psychosomatics |volume=78 |issue=5 |pages=265\u201374 |year=2009 |pmid=19602915 |doi=10.1159/000228247}}</ref>  and .69 for treating depression.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Driessen E, Cuijpers P, de Maat SC, Abbass AA, de Jonghe F, Dekker JJ |title=The efficacy of short-term psychodynamic psychotherapy for depression: a meta-analysis |journal=Clinical Psychology Review |volume=30 |issue=1 |pages=25\u201336 |date=February 2010  |pmid=19766369 |doi=10.1016/j.cpr.2009.08.010}}</ref> A 2012 meta-analysis by the ''[[Harvard Review of Psychiatry]]'' of Intensive Short-Term Dynamic Psychotherapy (ISTDP) found effect sizes ranging from .84 for interpersonal problems to 1.51 for depression. Overall ISTDP had an effect size of 1.18 compared to no treatment.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Abbass A, Town J, Driessen E |title=Intensive short-term dynamic psychotherapy: a systematic review and meta-analysis of outcome research |journal=Harvard Review of Psychiatry |volume=20 |issue=2 |pages=97\u2013108 |year=2012 |pmid=22512743 |doi=10.3109/10673229.2012.677347|citeseerx=10.1.1.668.6311 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, a study published in the American Journal of Psychiatry made 103 comparisons between psychodynamic treatment and a non-dynamic competitor and found that 6 were superior, 5 were inferior, 28 had no difference and 63 were adequate. The study found that this could be used as a basis \"to make psychodynamic psychotherapy an \"empirically validated\" treatment.\"<ref name=\"Gerber\">{{cite journal  |vauthors=Gerber AJ, Kocsis JH, Milrod BL, etal |title=A quality-based review of randomized controlled trials of psychodynamic psychotherapy |journal=The American Journal of Psychiatry |volume=168 |issue=1 |pages=19\u201328 |date=January 2011  |pmid=20843868 |doi=10.1176/appi.ajp.2010.08060843}}</ref>\n\nA 2011 meta study showed that long-term psychodynamic psychotherapy was superior to less intensive forms of psychotherapy in complex mental disorder. Depending upon severity of the underlying pathology, longer-term psychotherapy is required.  For example, individuals functioning at Level 1 of the DSM Personality Functioning Scale would require less treatment than one functioning at Level 2 or above. Studies have also demonstrated that those who received psychodynamic psychotherapy continued to grow post-therapy whereas those who received cognitive Behavior therapy did not.\n\n==Client-therapist relationship==\nBecause of the subjectivity of each client's potential psychological ailments, there is rarely a clear-cut treatment approach. Most often, therapists vary general approaches in order to best fit a client's specific needs. If a therapist does not understand the psychological ailments of their client extremely well, then it is unlikely that they are able to decide upon a treatment structure that will help the client. Therefore, the client-therapist relationship must be extremely strong. Therapists like their clients to be as open and honest as possible with them. Clients must trust their therapist if this is to happen. Because the effectiveness of treatment relies so heavily on the client giving information to their therapist, the client-therapist relationship is more vital to psychodynamic therapy than almost every other type of medical practice.<ref name=\"relationship\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1176/appi.ajp.160.7.1223|pmid=12832233|title=The Effectiveness of Psychodynamic Therapy and Cognitive Behavior Therapy in the Treatment of Personality Disorders: A Meta-Analysis|journal=American Journal of Psychiatry|volume=160|issue=7|pages=1223\u20131232|year=2003|last1=Leichsenring|first1=Falk|last2=Leibing|first2=Eric}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Anna Freud]]\n* [[Malan triangles]]\n* [[Models of abnormality]]\n* [[Psychodynamic Diagnostic Manual]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|28em}}\n\n{{Psychology}}\n{{Psychotherapy}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Psychodynamic Psychotherapy}}\n[[Category:Psychodynamics]]\n[[Category:Psychotherapy]]\n", "text_old": "{{Psychology sidebar}}\n{{Infobox interventions | MeshYear = 2014 | ICD10 = | ICD9 = | MeshID = D064889 | OPS301 = | OtherCodes = | = }}\n'''Psychodynamic psychotherapy''' or '''psychoanalytic psychotherapy'''<ref>British Psychoanalytic Council. (2018). [https://www.bpc.org.uk/about-psychotherapy/what-psychotherapy What is psychoanalytic psychotherapy?]</ref><ref>American Psychoanalytical Association (2018). [http://www.apsa.org/content/psychoanalytic-psychotherapy Psychoanalytic Psychotherapy]</ref> is a form of [[depth psychology]], the primary focus of which is to reveal the unconscious content of a client's psyche in an effort to alleviate psychic tension.<ref>[http://www.guidetopsychology.com/txtypes.htm#Psychodynamic Psychodynamic psychotherapy] - guidetopsychology.com</ref>\n\nPsychodynamic psychotherapy relies on the interpersonal relationship between client and therapist more than other forms of depth psychology. In terms of approach, this form of therapy uses psychoanalysis adapted to a less intensive style of working, usually at a frequency of once or twice per week. Principal theorists drawn upon are Freud, Klein, and theorists of the [[object relations theory|object relations movement]], e.g., Winnicott, Guntrip, and Bion. Some psychodynamic therapists also draw on [[Carl Jung|Jung]] or [[Jacques Lacan|Lacan]]. It is a focus that has been used in [[individual psychotherapy]], [[group psychotherapy]], [[family therapy]], and to understand and work with institutional and organizational contexts.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Granstr\u00f6m|first1=Kjell|title=Dynamik i arbetsgrupper|date=2006|publisher=[[Studentlitteratur]] |location=Lund|isbn=9789144008523|pages=197|edition=2}}</ref> In [[psychiatry]], it is considered a treatment of choice for [[adjustment disorders]], as well as [[posttraumatic stress disorder]] (PTSD) but more for personality-related disorders.<ref name=\"AgroninMaletta2006\">{{cite book|last1=Agronin|first1=Marc E.|last2=Maletta|first2=Gabe J.|title=Principles and Practice of Geriatric Psychiatry|year=2006|publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|language=English |isbn=9780781748100|page=423}}</ref><ref name=\"Corales2005\">{{cite book|last=Corales|first=Thomas A.|title=Trends in Posttraumatic Stress Disorder Research|year=2005|publisher=Nova Publishers|language=English |isbn=9781594541353|page=6}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe principles of [[psychodynamics]] were introduced in the 1874 publication ''Lectures on Physiology'' by German scientist [[Ernst Wilhelm von Br\u00fccke]]. Von Br\u00fccke, taking a cue from [[thermodynamics]], suggested all living organisms are energy systems, governed by the principle of [[Conservation of energy|energy conservation]]. During the same year, von Br\u00fccke was supervisor to first-year medical student [[Sigmund Freud]] at the [[University of Vienna]]. Freud later adopted this new construct of \u201cdynamic\u201d physiology to aid in his own conceptualization of the human psyche. Later, both the concept and application of psychodynamics were further developed by the likes of [[Carl Jung]], [[Alfred Adler]], [[Otto Rank]], and [[Melanie Klein]].<ref>[[Horacio Etchegoyen]]: ''The Fundamentals of Psychoanalytic Technique'', Karnac Books ed., New Ed, 2005, {{ISBN|1-85575-455-X}}{{page needed|date=December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Approaches==\n{{More citations needed section|date=April 2017}}\nMost psychodynamic approaches are centered on the concept that some maladaptive functioning is in play, and that this maladaption is, at least in part, [[Unconscious mind|unconscious]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Horowitz|first=Mardi J.|title=Introduction to psychodynamics: A new synthesis|publisher=Basic Books|year=1988}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1002/(sici)1097-4679(200006)56:6<723::aid-jclp3>3.0.co;2-3|title=Attributional style and defense mechanisms: A synthesis of cognitive and psychodynamic factors in depression|journal=Journal of Clinical Psychology|volume=56|issue=6|pages=723\u2013735|year=2000|last1=Kwon|first1=Paul|last2=Lemon|first2=Katherine E.}}</ref> The presumed maladaption develops early in life<ref>Lerner, H. \"Psychodynamic perspectives.\" The Handbook of Clinical Psychology 1 (2008): 127-160.</ref> and eventually causes difficulties in day-to-day life. Psychodynamic therapies focus on revealing and resolving these unconscious conflicts that are driving their symptoms.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1016/0272-7358(85)90047-9|title=Research on psychoanalytic psychodynamic propositions|journal=Clinical Psychology Review|volume=5|issue=3|pages=247\u2013257|year=1985|last1=Silverman|first1=Lloyd H.}}</ref> Major techniques used by psychodynamic therapists include [[Free association (psychology)|free association]], [[Interpretation of Dreams|dream interpretation]], recognizing resistance and [[transference]], working through painful memories and difficult issues, and building a strong therapeutic alliance. As in some psychoanalytic approaches, the therapeutic relationship is seen as a key means to understanding and working through the relational difficulties which the client has suffered in life.\n\n==Core principles and characteristics==\nAlthough psychodynamic psychotherapy can take many forms, commonalities include:<ref>{{cite book |last=Sundberg |first=Norman |title=Clinical Psychology: Evolving Theory, Practice, and Research |publisher=Prentice Hall |location=Englewood Cliffs |year=2001 |isbn=978-0-13-087119-0 }}{{page needed|date=December 2014}}</ref>\n* An emphasis on the centrality of intrapsychic and unconscious conflicts, and their relation to development\n* Identifying defenses as developing in internal psychic structures in order to avoid unpleasant consequences of conflict\n* A belief that psychopathology develops especially from early childhood experiences\n* A view that internal representations of experiences are organized around interpersonal relations\n* A conviction that life issues and dynamics will re-emerge in the context of the client-therapist relationship as [[transference]] and [[counter-transference]]\n* Use of [[Free association (psychology)|free association]] as a major method for exploration of internal conflicts and problems\n* Focusing on interpretations of [[transference]], defense mechanisms, and current symptoms and the [[working through]] of these present problems\n* Trust in [[insight]] as critically important for success in therapy\n\n==Efficacy==\nPsychodynamic psychotherapy, both short-term and long-term, is an effective psychotherapy. Psychodynamic psychotherapy is an evidence-based therapy (Schedler 2010) and its more intensive form, psychoanalysis has been proven to be evidence-based, also. Later meta-analyses showed psychoanalysis and psychodynamic therapy to be effective, with outcomes comparable or greater than other kinds of [[psychotherapy]] or [[antidepressant drugs]],<ref>{{cite journal |author=Shedler J |title=The efficacy of psychodynamic psychotherapy |journal=The American Psychologist |volume=65 |issue=2 |pages=98\u2013109 |year=2010 |pmid=20141265 |doi=10.1037/a0018378|citeseerx=10.1.1.607.2980 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Leichsenring F |title=Are psychodynamic and psychoanalytic therapies effective?: A review of empirical data |journal=The International Journal of Psycho-Analysis |volume=86 |issue=Pt 3 |pages=841\u201368 |date=June 2005  |pmid=16096078 |doi=10.1516/rfee-lkpn-b7tf-kpdu}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid21719877\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Leichsenring F, Rabung S |title=Long-term psychodynamic psychotherapy in complex mental disorders: update of a meta-analysis |journal=The British Journal of Psychiatry |volume=199 |issue=1 |pages=15\u201322 |date=July 2011  |pmid=21719877 |doi=10.1192/bjp.bp.110.082776}}</ref> but these arguments have also been subjected to various criticisms.<ref>{{cite journal |author=McKay D |title=Methods and mechanisms in the efficacy of psychodynamic psychotherapy |journal=The American Psychologist |volume=66 |issue=2 |pages=147\u20138; discussion 152\u20134 |year=2011 |pmid=21299262 |doi=10.1037/a0021195|url=https://fordham.bepress.com/psych_facultypubs/318 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Thombs BD, Jewett LR, Bassel M |title=Is there room for criticism of studies of psychodynamic psychotherapy? |journal=The American Psychologist |volume=66 |issue=2 |pages=148\u20139; discussion 152\u20134 |year=2011 |pmid=21299263 |doi=10.1037/a0021248}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Anestis MD, Anestis JC, Lilienfeld SO |title=When it comes to evaluating psychodynamic therapy, the devil is in the details |journal=The American Psychologist |volume=66 |issue=2 |pages=149\u201351; discussion 152\u20134 |year=2011 |pmid=21299264 |doi=10.1037/a0021190}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Tryon WW, Tryon GS |title=No ownership of common factors |journal=The American Psychologist |volume=66 |issue=2 |pages=151\u20132; discussion 152\u20134 |year=2011 |pmid=21299265 |doi=10.1037/a0021056}}</ref> For example, [[Meta-analyses]] in 2012 and 2013 came to the conclusion that there is little support or evidence for the efficacy of psychoanalytic therapy, thus further research is needed<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Leichsenring F, Abbass A, Luyten P, Hilsenroth M, Rabung S |title=The emerging evidence for long-term psychodynamic therapy |journal=Psychodynamic Psychiatry |volume=41 |issue=3 |pages=361\u201384 |year=2013 |pmid=24001160 |doi=10.1521/pdps.2013.41.3.361}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal  |vauthors=de Maat S, de Jonghe F, de Kraker R, etal |title=The current state of the empirical evidence for psychoanalysis: a meta-analytic approach |journal=Harvard Review of Psychiatry |volume=21 |issue=3 |pages=107\u201337 |year=2013 |pmid=23660968 |doi=10.1097/HRP.0b013e318294f5fd|doi-broken-date=2019-12-11 |url=https://journals.lww.com/hrpjournal/fulltext/2013/05000/The_Current_State_of_the_Empirical_Evidence_for.1.aspx}}</ref>.\n\nA system review of Long Term Psychodynamic Psychotherapy (LTPP) in 2009 found an overall effect size of .33.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Smit Y, Huibers MJ, Ioannidis JP, van Dyck R, van Tilburg W, Arntz A |title=The effectiveness of long-term psychoanalytic psychotherapy--a meta-analysis of randomized controlled trials |journal=Clinical Psychology Review |volume=32 |issue=2 |pages=81\u201392 |date=March 2012  |pmid=22227111 |doi=10.1016/j.cpr.2011.11.003}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> Others have found effect sizes of .44\u2013.68.<ref name=\"pmid21719877\" />\n\nMeta-analyses of Short Term Psychodynamic Psychotherapy (STPP) have found effect sizes ranging from .34\u2013.71 compared to no treatment and was found to be slightly better than other therapies in follow up.<ref>{{cite journal |first1=Edward M. |last1=Anderson |first2=Michael J. |last2=Lambert |title=Short-term dynamically oriented psychotherapy: A review and meta-analysis |journal=Clinical Psychology Review |volume=15 |issue=6 |year=1995 |pages=503\u201314 |doi=10.1016/0272-7358(95)00027-M}}</ref> Other reviews have found an effect size of .78\u2013.91 for [[Somatoform disorder|somatic disorders]] compared to no treatment<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Abbass A, Kisely S, Kroenke K |title=Short-term psychodynamic psychotherapy for somatic disorders. Systematic review and meta-analysis of clinical trials |journal=Psychotherapy and Psychosomatics |volume=78 |issue=5 |pages=265\u201374 |year=2009 |pmid=19602915 |doi=10.1159/000228247}}</ref>  and .69 for treating depression.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Driessen E, Cuijpers P, de Maat SC, Abbass AA, de Jonghe F, Dekker JJ |title=The efficacy of short-term psychodynamic psychotherapy for depression: a meta-analysis |journal=Clinical Psychology Review |volume=30 |issue=1 |pages=25\u201336 |date=February 2010  |pmid=19766369 |doi=10.1016/j.cpr.2009.08.010}}</ref> A 2012 meta-analysis by the ''[[Harvard Review of Psychiatry]]'' of Intensive Short-Term Dynamic Psychotherapy (ISTDP) found effect sizes ranging from .84 for interpersonal problems to 1.51 for depression. Overall ISTDP had an effect size of 1.18 compared to no treatment.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Abbass A, Town J, Driessen E |title=Intensive short-term dynamic psychotherapy: a systematic review and meta-analysis of outcome research |journal=Harvard Review of Psychiatry |volume=20 |issue=2 |pages=97\u2013108 |year=2012 |pmid=22512743 |doi=10.3109/10673229.2012.677347|citeseerx=10.1.1.668.6311 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, a study published in the American Journal of Psychiatry made 103 comparisons between psychodynamic treatment and a non-dynamic competitor and found that 6 were superior, 5 were inferior, 28 had no difference and 63 were adequate. The study found that this could be used as a basis \"to make psychodynamic psychotherapy an \"empirically validated\" treatment.\"<ref name=\"Gerber\">{{cite journal  |vauthors=Gerber AJ, Kocsis JH, Milrod BL, etal |title=A quality-based review of randomized controlled trials of psychodynamic psychotherapy |journal=The American Journal of Psychiatry |volume=168 |issue=1 |pages=19\u201328 |date=January 2011  |pmid=20843868 |doi=10.1176/appi.ajp.2010.08060843}}</ref>\n\nA 2011 meta study showing that long-term psychodynamic psychotherapy was superior to less intensive forms of psychotherapy in complex mental disorder. Depending upon severity of the underlying pathology, longer-term psychotherapy is required.  For example, individuals functioning at Level 1 of the DSM Personality Functioning Scale would require less treatment than one functioning at Level 2 or above. Studies have also demonstrated that those who received psychodynamic psychotherapy continued to grow post-therapy whereas those who received cognitive Behavior therapy did not.\n\n==Client-therapist relationship==\nBecause of the subjectivity of each client's potential psychological ailments, there is rarely a clear-cut treatment approach. Most often, therapists vary general approaches in order to best fit a client's specific needs. If a therapist does not understand the psychological ailments of their client extremely well, then it is unlikely that they are able to decide upon a treatment structure that will help the client. Therefore, the client-therapist relationship must be extremely strong. Therapists like their clients to be as open and honest as possible with them. Clients must trust their therapist if this is to happen. Because the effectiveness of treatment relies so heavily on the client giving information to their therapist, the client-therapist relationship is more vital to psychodynamic therapy than almost every other type of medical practice.<ref name=\"relationship\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1176/appi.ajp.160.7.1223|pmid=12832233|title=The Effectiveness of Psychodynamic Therapy and Cognitive Behavior Therapy in the Treatment of Personality Disorders: A Meta-Analysis|journal=American Journal of Psychiatry|volume=160|issue=7|pages=1223\u20131232|year=2003|last1=Leichsenring|first1=Falk|last2=Leibing|first2=Eric}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Anna Freud]]\n* [[Malan triangles]]\n* [[Models of abnormality]]\n* [[Psychodynamic Diagnostic Manual]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|28em}}\n\n{{Psychology}}\n{{Psychotherapy}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Psychodynamic Psychotherapy}}\n[[Category:Psychodynamics]]\n[[Category:Psychotherapy]]\n", "name_user": "Mentropane", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEfficacy", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Psychodynamic_psychotherapy"}
{"title_page": "Second Azarov government", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox government cabinet\n|cabinet_name = Second Azarov Government\n|cabinet_number = 15th\n|jurisdiction = Ukraine (since 1990)\n|incumbent = \n|image = Second Azarov government.jpg\n|image_size = 275px\n|date_formed = December 24, 2012\n|date_dissolved = January 28, 2014\n|government_head = [[Mykola Azarov]]\n|government_head_history =\n|deputy_government_head = [[Serhiy Arbuzov]]\n|state_head = [[Viktor Yanukovych]]\n|current_number = 23\n|former_members_number =\n|total_number =\n|political_party = [[Party of Regions]]<br />[[Ukraine \u2013 Forward!]]\n|legislature_status = Majority\n|election = \n|last_election =\n|legislature_term = \n|budget = \n|opposition_cabinet = \n|opposition_party = [[All-Ukrainian Union \"Fatherland\"|Batkivshchyna]]<br />[[Ukrainian Democratic Alliance for Reform|UDAR]]<br />[[All-Ukrainian Union \"Svoboda\"|Svoboda]]\n|opposition_leader = [[Arseniy Yatsenyuk]]<br />[[Vitaliy Klychko]]<br />[[Oleh Tyahnybok]]\n|incoming_formation =\n|outgoing_formation =\n|previous = [[First Azarov government]]\n|successor = [[First Yatsenyuk government]]\n}}\n{{Politics of Ukraine (small)}}\nThe '''second Azarov government''' ({{lang-uk|\u0414\u0440\u0443\u0433\u0438\u0439 \u0443\u0440\u044f\u0434 \u041c\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0438 \u0410\u0437\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430}} ''Druhyi uryad Mykoly Azarova'') was Ukraine's government from December 24, 2012 to January 28, 2014.<ref name=USMG241212a>[http://www.unian.info/news/543116-yanukovych-appoints-new-staff-of-cabinet-of-ministers-of-ukraine.html President of Ukraine has appointed new staff of the Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131211161007/http://www.unian.info/news/543116-yanukovych-appoints-new-staff-of-cabinet-of-ministers-of-ukraine.html |date=11 December 2013 }}, [[UNIAN]] (24 December 2012)</ref> It was dissolved during the [[Euromaidan]] protests.<ref>https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/ukrainian-prime-minister-resigns-as-unrest-continues/article16540544/</ref> The ministers (except Prime Minister [[Mykola Azarov]] who was replaced by Deputy Prime Minister [[Serhiy Arbuzov]] (ex officio),<ref name=EN28114AA/> continued shortly as a caretaker government.<ref name=EN28114AA/><ref name=60dcsag/> On 27 February 2014 Ukraine's parliament approved a resolution to dismiss the government.<ref name=Afg27214>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/193220.html Rada dismisses previous government, to form new one], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (27 February 2014)</ref>\n\n==Creation==\nOn 3 December 2012, the [[first Azarov government]] became a [[caretaker government]] after [[Ukrainian president]] [[Viktor Yanukovich]] accepted the resignation of prime minister Mykola Azarov and his government following the [[2012 Ukrainian parliamentary election|28 October 2012 parliamentary election]].<ref name=caretKP31212>[http://www.kyivpost.com/content/politics/yanukovych-dismisses-azarov-and-cabinet-of-ministers-317066.html Yanukovych dismisses Azarov and Cabinet of Ministers], [[Kyiv Post]] (3 December 2012)<br />[http://www.kyivpost.com/content/politics/ukraine-government-resigns-stays-on-in-acting-role-317068.html Ukraine government resigns, stays on in acting role], ''[[Kyiv Post]]'' (3 December 2012)</ref> A number of government members, including Prime Minister Azarov, were elected to parliament in that election.<ref name=caretKP31212/> In order to get these parliamentary mandates, they were obliged to submit documents on the dismissal from their previous job to the [[Central Election Commission of Ukraine|Central Election Commission]] within 20 days after the election (by 3 December).<ref>[http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/baloha-posts-his-resignation-as-emergencies-minister-on-facebook-316808.html Baloha posts his resignation as emergencies minister on Facebook], [[Kyiv Post]] (27 November 2012)</ref>\n\nOn 9 December 2012, Yanukovych nominated Azarov for a new term as prime minister.<ref>[http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/ukraine-leader-picks-prime-minister-azarov-for-new-term-in-post-317367.html Yanukovych picks Azarov for new term as prime minister (updated)], [[Kyiv Post]] (9 December 2012)</ref> This nomination was approved by parliament on 13 December 2012.<ref name=PMAzarovA>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/12/13/ukraine-pm-idUSL5E8ND8QN20121213 Ukraine parliament approves Azarov as prime minister], [[Reuters]] (13 December 2012)</ref> According to Svoboda, that voted absolutely against Azarov, his appointment is illegal at least due to such technicality in the law of Ukraine which requires the [[president of Ukraine]] to be physically present in the session hall of parliament during his candidacy approval by [[Verkhovna Rada]].<ref name=\"second_day\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MPqq2PRpPW4#! The second day of work. Verkhovna Rada 7.]. Youtube by Svoboda. 14 December 2012</ref> The [[People's Deputy of Ukraine]] from the parliamentary faction [[UDAR]], [[Iryna Herashchenko]], stated that the all political appointments that took place that day are a \"political bribe\" of the party of power ([[Party of Regions]]) to the [[Communist Party of Ukraine]].<ref name=\"second_day\"/> On 4 December 2012, nine days before appointment of Azarov, a people's deputy of Ukraine from Communist Party of Ukraine [[Spiridon Kilinkarov]] insisted at the political talk show ''Syohodni. Pro holovne'' on the Ukrainian television channel [[TVi (channel)|TVi]] that communists absolutely will not vote for any candidates to the [[prime minister of Ukraine]] from [[Party of Regions]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=h4ogs5cxHSc CPU: We are not going to vote for the Prime Minister of Party of Regions]. Youtube. 13 December 2012</ref> On 13 December, absolutely all members of the Communist Party of Ukraine voted as one for the candidacy of [[Mykola Azarov]] as the Prime Minister of Ukraine.\n\nOn 24 December 2012, the second Azarov government was appointed by president Yanukovych (Presidential Ukase #726/2012<ref name=\"ukase\">[http://www.president.gov.ua/documents/15236.html Official document: Presidential Ukase #726] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121230184341/http://www.president.gov.ua/documents/15236.html |date=30 December 2012}}. Website of the President of Ukraine. 24 December 2012</ref>).<ref name=USMG241212a/> The coalition of Party of Regions and [[Ukraine \u2013 Forward!]] as it is now in the government was foreseen and mentioned by the Ukrainian television studio [[Kvartal 95]] in October 2012 in one of their episodes of [[Evening quarter]].<ref>{{YouTube|ROQu36CeXe4|\"Evening quarter\". The first three of \"Ukraine \u2013 Forward!\"}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Anders \u00c5slund]], the government faced three big tasks: to govern, to break Ukraine\u2019s foreign isolation and to salvage the country from a vulnerable financial situation.<ref name=\"\u00c5slundKP251212\"/> In December 2012, he observed \"little reason to believe that it can solve any of these three tasks\".<ref name=\"\u00c5slundKP251212\">[http://www.kyivpost.com/opinion/op-ed/ukraines-new-government-sign-of-increasing-yanukovych-weakness-2-318134.html Ukraine\u2019s new government sign of increasing Yanukovych weakness], [[Kyiv Post]] (25 December 2012)</ref>\n\nCommunist Party faction leader [[Petro Symonenko]] stated on 28 December 2012 that the Communist Party of Ukraine and the Party of Regions had not concluded any agreements concerning the Communist support of Mykola Azarov's candidacy for the post of Prime Minister but that his party had supported this nomination because Azarov had told them his government was ready to implement the program on Ukraine's accession to the [[Customs Union of Belarus, Kazakhstan and Russia]].<ref name=SsAKP281212/> Symonenko added that should Azarov fail to fulfill the promise of Ukraine's joining this customs union, the Communists would initiate his resignation.<ref name=SsAKP281212>[http://www.kyivpost.com/content/politics/symonenko-communist-party-had-no-agreements-to-support-azarovs-candidacy-for-premiership-318254.html Symonenko:Communist Party had no agreements to support Azarov's candidacy for premiership], ''[[Kyiv Post]]'' (28 December 2012)</ref>\n\n===Parliamentary voting===\n{| align=\"center\" class=\"standard\"\n|+\n! |'''Yes'''\n! |No\n! |Abstained\n! |Did not vote\n! |'''Total'''\n|-----\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''252'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 129\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 20\n|align=center| 401\n|+\n|}\n\n{| align=\"center\" class=\"standard\"\n|+\n! |Faction\n! |Number of members\n! |'''Yes'''\n! |No\n! |Abstained\n! |Did not vote\n! |Absent\n|-----\n| '''[[Party of Regions]]'''\n|align=center bgcolor=#AAEEFF| 210\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''208'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 2\n|-----\n| '''[[All-Ukrainian Union \"Fatherland\"|Batkivshchyna \u2013 United Opposition]]'''\n|align=center bgcolor=#FFFFAA| 99\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''0'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 51\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 16\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 32\n|-----\n| '''[[Ukrainian Democratic Alliance for Reform|UDAR]]'''\n|align=center bgcolor=#DE3163| 42\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''0'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"|38\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 3\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 1\n|-----\n| '''[[All-Ukrainian Union \"Svoboda\"|Svoboda]]'''\n|align=center bgcolor=#0095B6| 37\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''0'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 37\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 0\n|-----\n| '''[[Communist Party of Ukraine]]'''\n|align=center bgcolor=#FFAAAA| 32\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''32'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 0\n|-----\n| Not affiliated\n|align=center| 24\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''12'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 3\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 1\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 8\n|+\n|}\n\n===Vote of no confidence===\nIn 2013 the government managed twice to survive the vote of no confidence from the [[Ukrainian parliament]] until finally the [[president of Ukraine]] accepted the resignation of [[prime minister of Ukraine]] [[Mykola Azarov]] earlier in 2014.\n\nThe first time the parliament voted on April 19, 2013.<ref>[http://w1.c1.rada.gov.ua/pls/radan_gs09/ns_golos?g_id=972 Individual voting]. [[Verkhovna Rada]]. April 19, 2013</ref>\n\n{| align=\"center\" class=\"standard\"\n|+\n! |'''Yes'''\n! |No\n! |Abstained\n! |Did not vote\n! |'''Total'''\n|-----\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''190'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 91\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 2\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 79\n|align=center| 362\n|+\n|}\n\n{| align=\"center\" class=\"standard\"\n|+\n! |Faction\n! |Number of members\n! |'''Yes'''\n! |No\n! |Abstained\n! |Did not vote\n! |Absent\n|-----\n| '''[[Party of Regions]]'''\n|align=center bgcolor=#AAEEFF| 207\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''0'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 91\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 2\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 74\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 40\n|-----\n| '''[[All-Ukrainian Union \"Fatherland\"|Batkivshchyna \u2013 United Opposition]]'''\n|align=center bgcolor=#FFFFAA| 95\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''88'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 7\n|-----\n| '''[[Ukrainian Democratic Alliance for Reform|UDAR]]'''\n|align=center bgcolor=#DE3163| 42\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''35'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 7\n|-----\n| '''[[All-Ukrainian Union \"Svoboda\"|Svoboda]]'''\n|align=center bgcolor=#0095B6| 36\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''36'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 0\n|-----\n| '''[[Communist Party of Ukraine]]'''\n|align=center bgcolor=#FFAAAA| 32\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''21'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 1\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 10\n|-----\n| Not affiliated\n|align=center| 32\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''10'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 4\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 18\n|+\n|}\n\nThe second time the parliament voted on December 3, 2013.<ref>[http://w1.c1.rada.gov.ua/pls/radan_gs09/ns_golos?g_id=3409 Individual voting]. [[Verkhovna Rada]]. December 3, 2013</ref>\n\n{| align=\"center\" class=\"standard\"\n|+\n! |'''Yes'''\n! |No\n! |Abstained\n! |Did not vote\n! |'''Total'''\n|-----\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''186'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 5\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 12\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 135\n|align=center| 338\n|+\n|}\n\n{| align=\"center\" class=\"standard\"\n|+\n! |Faction\n! |Number of members\n! |'''Yes'''\n! |No\n! |Abstained\n! |Did not vote\n! |Absent\n|-----\n| '''[[Party of Regions]]'''\n|align=center bgcolor=#AAEEFF| 205\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''1'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 5\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 12\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 100\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 87\n|-----\n| '''[[All-Ukrainian Union \"Fatherland\"|Batkivshchyna \u2013 United Opposition]]'''\n|align=center bgcolor=#FFFFAA| 90\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''90'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 0\n|-----\n| '''[[Ukrainian Democratic Alliance for Reform|UDAR]]'''\n|align=center bgcolor=#DE3163| 42\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''42'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 0\n|-----\n| '''[[All-Ukrainian Union \"Svoboda\"|Svoboda]]'''\n|align=center bgcolor=#0095B6| 36\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''36'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 0\n|-----\n| '''[[Communist Party of Ukraine]]'''\n|align=center bgcolor=#FFAAAA| 31\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''0'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 31\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 0\n|-----\n| Not affiliated\n|align=center| 38\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''17'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 4\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 17\n|+\n|}\n\n==Fall and temporary continuation as caretaker cabinet==\nAfter weeks of [[Euromaidan]] protests, and [[2014 Hrushevskoho Street riots|clashes, during which civilians were killed]]{{#tag:ref|The [[Ministry of Internal Affairs of Ukraine]] claimed on 25 January 2014 that a policeman who was walking home in civilian clothing had been killed by a shot in his head.<ref name=psdIU25114>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/187390.html Policeman shot dead in Kyiv, another policeman sustains knife wound - Ukrainian interior ministry], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (25 January 2014)</ref>|group=nb}}, Prime Minister Azarov offered his letter of resignation on 28 January 2014.<ref name=BBCNews2014a>{{cite news|title=Ukraine's PM Azarov and government resign|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-25932352|accessdate=28 January 2014|date=28 January 2014|author=BBC News}}</ref> According to his cabinet, Azarov was quoted saying that \"In order to create additional opportunities for socio-political compromise, for the sake of the peaceful settlement of the conflict, I have made a personal decision to ask the Ukrainian president to accept my resignation from the post of Ukrainian prime minister\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/187663.html|title=Ukrainian Prime Minister Azarov resigns|author=|date=|work=Interfax.com.ua|access-date=18 March 2017}}</ref> Under the [[Ukrainian constitution]] this meant the whole government had resigned.<ref name=EN28114AA/> The president subsequently accepted the resignation and signed a decree dismissing the cabinet, which decree would not take effect until the Verhovna Rada approved a new cabinet. Hence the second Azarov government continued as a caretaker government.<ref name=EN28114AA/> Prime Minister Azarov was replaced by deputy prime minister [[Serhiy Arbuzov]].<ref name=EN28114AA>[http://www.euronews.com/2014/01/28/ukrainian-parliament-votes-to-scrap-controversial-anti-protest-laws/ Ukrainian parliament delays vote on amnesty law until Wednesday], [[Euronews]] (28 January 2014)</ref> But under Ukrainian law the cabinet could be able to implement its duties for no more than 60 days.<ref name=60dcsag>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/188961.html Serhiy Arbuzov to head Ukraine govt pending premier's appointment], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (6 February 2014)</ref>\n\nThe [[February 2014 Euromaidan riots#Deal|compromise deal of February 21, 2014, between president Yanukovych and the opposition]] to end the [[February 2014 Euromaidan riots]] stipulated that a new [[national unity government]] was to be formed within ten days.<ref name=DTU21214>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/10655129/Ukraine-peace-hopes-in-the-air-as-president-loses-his-powers.html Ukraine: peace hopes in the air as president loses his powers], ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' (21 February 2014)</ref> On 27 February 2014 Ukraine's parliament approved a resolution to dismiss the government.<ref name=Afg27214/> They immediately followed it by the appointment of the new cabinet members of the [[First Yatsenyuk government|Yatsenyuk government]].<ref name=IU26214GNU>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/193035.html Maidan nominates Yatseniuk for prime minister], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (26 February 2014)<br />[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/193222.html Ukrainian parliament endorses new cabinet], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (27 February 2014)</ref>\n\n==Achievements==\nIn December 2013 the [[IMF]] stated that the Ukrainian government's policy mix had \"generated large external and fiscal imbalances\" and that this had \"contributed to deepening the recession in the country\".<ref>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/183061.html IMF slams Ukraine's macroeconomic policy], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (20 December 2013)</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n{{Azarov Government Two}}\n\n===Vice prime minister assignments===\n* First Vice PM \u2013 Serhiy Arbuzov\n** Ministry of Agrarian Policy and Food\n** Ministry of Economical Development and Trade\n** Ministry of Social Policy\n** Ministry of Finance\n** Ministry of Revenues and Duties\n* Vice PM \u2013 Yuri Boiko<ref name=Boiko/>\n** Ministry of Energy and Coal Industry\n** Ministry of Ecology and Natural Resources\n** Ministry of Industrial Policy\n**[[Space program of Ukraine|Space sector]]\n* Vice PM \u2013 Oleksandr Vilkul\n** Ministry of Infrastructure\n** Ministry of Regional Development, Construction and Housing\n* Vice PM \u2013 Kostyantyn Hryshchenko\n** Ministry of Culture\n** Ministry of Education and Science, Youth and Sport\n** Ministry of Health Security\n* Non-supervised ministries ([[National Security and Defense Council of Ukraine]])\n** Ministry of Justice\n** Ministry of Defense\n** Ministry of Foreign Affairs\n** Ministry of Internal Affairs\n** Ministry of Cabinet of Ministers\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|group=nb}}\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.kmu.gov.ua Governmental Portal of Ukraine] \u2013 official site of the Cabinet of Ministers\n\n{{Cabinets of Ukraine}}\n{{Politics of Ukraine footer}}\n{{Euromaidan}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Azarov, Mykola}}\n[[Category:Ukrainian governments]]\n[[Category:Cabinets established in 2012]]\n[[Category:2012 establishments in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:2014 disestablishments in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Cabinets disestablished in 2014]]\n[[Category:Euromaidan]]\n[[Category:7th Ukrainian Verkhovna Rada|Azarov]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox government cabinet\n|cabinet_name = Second Azarov Government\n|cabinet_number = 15th\n|jurisdiction = Ukraine (since 1990)\n|incumbent = \n|image = Second Azarov government.jpg\n|image_size = 275px\n|date_formed = December 24, 2012\n|date_dissolved = January 28, 2014\n|government_head = [[Mykola Azarov]]\n|government_head_history =\n|deputy_government_head = [[Serhiy Arbuzov]]\n|state_head = [[Viktor Yanukovych]]\n|current_number = 23\n|former_members_number =\n|total_number =\n|political_party = [[Party of Regions]]<br />[[Ukraine \u2013 Forward!]]\n|legislature_status = Majority\n|election = \n|last_election =\n|legislature_term = \n|budget = \n|opposition_cabinet = \n|opposition_party = [[All-Ukrainian Union \"Fatherland\"|Batkivshchyna]]<br />[[Ukrainian Democratic Alliance for Reform|UDAR]]<br />[[All-Ukrainian Union \"Svoboda\"|Svoboda]]\n|opposition_leader = [[Arseniy Yatsenyuk]]<br />[[Vitaliy Klychko]]<br />[[Oleh Tyahnybok]]\n|incoming_formation =\n|outgoing_formation =\n|previous = [[First Azarov government]]\n|successor = [[First Yatsenyuk government]]\n}}\n{{Politics of Ukraine (small)}}\nThe '''second Azarov government''' ({{lang-uk|\u0414\u0440\u0443\u0433\u0438\u0439 \u0443\u0440\u044f\u0434 \u041c\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0438 \u0410\u0437\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430}} ''Druhyi uryad Mykoly Azarova'') was Ukraine's government from December 24, 2012 to January 28, 2014.<ref name=USMG241212>[http://www.unian.info/news/543116-yanukovych-appoints-new-staff-of-cabinet-of-ministers-of-ukraine.html President of Ukraine has appointed new staff of the Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131211161007/http://www.unian.info/news/543116-yanukovych-appoints-new-staff-of-cabinet-of-ministers-of-ukraine.html |date=11 December 2013 }}, [[UNIAN]] (24 December 2012)</ref> It was dissolved during the [[Euromaidan]] protests.<ref>https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/ukrainian-prime-minister-resigns-as-unrest-continues/article16540544/</ref> The ministers (except Prime Minister [[Mykola Azarov]] who was replaced by Deputy Prime Minister [[Serhiy Arbuzov]] (ex officio),<ref name=EN28114AA/> continued shortly as a caretaker government.<ref name=EN28114AA/><ref name=60dcsag/> On 27 February 2014 Ukraine's parliament approved a resolution to dismiss the government.<ref name=Afg27214>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/193220.html Rada dismisses previous government, to form new one], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (27 February 2014)</ref>\n\n==Creation==\nOn 3 December 2012, the [[first Azarov government]] became a [[caretaker government]] after [[Ukrainian president]] [[Viktor Yanukovich]] accepted the resignation of prime minister Mykola Azarov and his government following the [[2012 Ukrainian parliamentary election|28 October 2012 parliamentary election]].<ref name=caretKP31212>[http://www.kyivpost.com/content/politics/yanukovych-dismisses-azarov-and-cabinet-of-ministers-317066.html Yanukovych dismisses Azarov and Cabinet of Ministers], [[Kyiv Post]] (3 December 2012)<br />[http://www.kyivpost.com/content/politics/ukraine-government-resigns-stays-on-in-acting-role-317068.html Ukraine government resigns, stays on in acting role], ''[[Kyiv Post]]'' (3 December 2012)</ref> A number of government members, including Prime Minister Azarov, were elected to parliament in that election.<ref name=caretKP31212/> In order to get these parliamentary mandates, they were obliged to submit documents on the dismissal from their previous job to the [[Central Election Commission of Ukraine|Central Election Commission]] within 20 days after the election (by 3 December).<ref>[http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/baloha-posts-his-resignation-as-emergencies-minister-on-facebook-316808.html Baloha posts his resignation as emergencies minister on Facebook], [[Kyiv Post]] (27 November 2012)</ref>\n\nOn 9 December 2012, Yanukovych nominated Azarov for a new term as prime minister.<ref>[http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/ukraine-leader-picks-prime-minister-azarov-for-new-term-in-post-317367.html Yanukovych picks Azarov for new term as prime minister (updated)], [[Kyiv Post]] (9 December 2012)</ref> This nomination was approved by parliament on 13 December 2012.<ref name=PMAzarovA>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/12/13/ukraine-pm-idUSL5E8ND8QN20121213 Ukraine parliament approves Azarov as prime minister], [[Reuters]] (13 December 2012)</ref> According to Svoboda, that voted absolutely against Azarov, his appointment is illegal at least due to such technicality in the law of Ukraine which requires the [[president of Ukraine]] to be physically present in the session hall of parliament during his candidacy approval by [[Verkhovna Rada]].<ref name=\"second_day\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MPqq2PRpPW4#! The second day of work. Verkhovna Rada 7.]. Youtube by Svoboda. 14 December 2012</ref> The [[People's Deputy of Ukraine]] from the parliamentary faction [[UDAR]], [[Iryna Herashchenko]], stated that the all political appointments that took place that day are a \"political bribe\" of the party of power ([[Party of Regions]]) to the [[Communist Party of Ukraine]].<ref name=\"second_day\"/> On 4 December 2012, nine days before appointment of Azarov, a people's deputy of Ukraine from Communist Party of Ukraine [[Spiridon Kilinkarov]] insisted at the political talk show ''Syohodni. Pro holovne'' on the Ukrainian television channel [[TVi (channel)|TVi]] that communists absolutely will not vote for any candidates to the [[prime minister of Ukraine]] from [[Party of Regions]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=h4ogs5cxHSc CPU: We are not going to vote for the Prime Minister of Party of Regions]. Youtube. 13 December 2012</ref> On 13 December, absolutely all members of the Communist Party of Ukraine voted as one for the candidacy of [[Mykola Azarov]] as the Prime Minister of Ukraine.\n\nOn 24 December 2012, the second Azarov government was appointed by president Yanukovych (Presidential Ukase #726/2012<ref name=\"ukase\">[http://www.president.gov.ua/documents/15236.html Official document: Presidential Ukase #726] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121230184341/http://www.president.gov.ua/documents/15236.html |date=30 December 2012 }}. Website of the President of Ukraine. 24 December 2012</ref>).<ref name=USMG241212/> The coalition of Party of Regions and [[Ukraine \u2013 Forward!]] as it is now in the government was foreseen and mentioned by the Ukrainian television studio [[Kvartal 95]] in October 2012 in one of their episodes of [[Evening quarter]].<ref>{{YouTube|ROQu36CeXe4|\"Evening quarter\". The first three of \"Ukraine \u2013 Forward!\"}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Anders \u00c5slund]], the government faced three big tasks: to govern, to break Ukraine\u2019s foreign isolation and to salvage the country from a vulnerable financial situation.<ref name=\"\u00c5slundKP251212\"/> In December 2012, he observed \"little reason to believe that it can solve any of these three tasks\".<ref name=\"\u00c5slundKP251212\">[http://www.kyivpost.com/opinion/op-ed/ukraines-new-government-sign-of-increasing-yanukovych-weakness-2-318134.html Ukraine\u2019s new government sign of increasing Yanukovych weakness], [[Kyiv Post]] (25 December 2012)</ref>\n\nCommunist Party faction leader [[Petro Symonenko]] stated on 28 December 2012 that the Communist Party of Ukraine and the Party of Regions had not concluded any agreements concerning the Communist support of Mykola Azarov's candidacy for the post of Prime Minister but that his party had supported this nomination because Azarov had told them his government was ready to implement the program on Ukraine's accession to the [[Customs Union of Belarus, Kazakhstan and Russia]].<ref name=SsAKP281212/> Symonenko added that should Azarov fail to fulfill the promise of Ukraine's joining this customs union, the Communists would initiate his resignation.<ref name=SsAKP281212>[http://www.kyivpost.com/content/politics/symonenko-communist-party-had-no-agreements-to-support-azarovs-candidacy-for-premiership-318254.html Symonenko:Communist Party had no agreements to support Azarov's candidacy for premiership], ''[[Kyiv Post]]'' (28 December 2012)</ref>\n\n===Parliamentary voting===\n{| align=\"center\" class=\"standard\"\n|+\n! |'''Yes'''\n! |No\n! |Abstained\n! |Did not vote\n! |'''Total'''\n|-----\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''252'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 129\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 20\n|align=center| 401\n|+\n|}\n\n{| align=\"center\" class=\"standard\"\n|+\n! |Faction\n! |Number of members\n! |'''Yes'''\n! |No\n! |Abstained\n! |Did not vote\n! |Absent\n|-----\n| '''[[Party of Regions]]'''\n|align=center bgcolor=#AAEEFF| 210\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''208'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 2\n|-----\n| '''[[All-Ukrainian Union \"Fatherland\"|Batkivshchyna \u2013 United Opposition]]'''\n|align=center bgcolor=#FFFFAA| 99\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''0'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 51\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 16\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 32\n|-----\n| '''[[Ukrainian Democratic Alliance for Reform|UDAR]]'''\n|align=center bgcolor=#DE3163| 42\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''0'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"|38\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 3\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 1\n|-----\n| '''[[All-Ukrainian Union \"Svoboda\"|Svoboda]]'''\n|align=center bgcolor=#0095B6| 37\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''0'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 37\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 0\n|-----\n| '''[[Communist Party of Ukraine]]'''\n|align=center bgcolor=#FFAAAA| 32\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''32'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 0\n|-----\n| Not affiliated\n|align=center| 24\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''12'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 3\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 1\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 8\n|+\n|}\n\n===Vote of no confidence===\nIn 2013 the government managed twice to survive the vote of no confidence from the [[Ukrainian parliament]] until finally the [[president of Ukraine]] accepted the resignation of [[prime minister of Ukraine]] [[Mykola Azarov]] earlier in 2014.\n\nThe first time the parliament voted on April 19, 2013.<ref>[http://w1.c1.rada.gov.ua/pls/radan_gs09/ns_golos?g_id=972 Individual voting]. [[Verkhovna Rada]]. April 19, 2013</ref>\n\n{| align=\"center\" class=\"standard\"\n|+\n! |'''Yes'''\n! |No\n! |Abstained\n! |Did not vote\n! |'''Total'''\n|-----\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''190'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 91\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 2\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 79\n|align=center| 362\n|+\n|}\n\n{| align=\"center\" class=\"standard\"\n|+\n! |Faction\n! |Number of members\n! |'''Yes'''\n! |No\n! |Abstained\n! |Did not vote\n! |Absent\n|-----\n| '''[[Party of Regions]]'''\n|align=center bgcolor=#AAEEFF| 207\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''0'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 91\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 2\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 74\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 40\n|-----\n| '''[[All-Ukrainian Union \"Fatherland\"|Batkivshchyna \u2013 United Opposition]]'''\n|align=center bgcolor=#FFFFAA| 95\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''88'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 7\n|-----\n| '''[[Ukrainian Democratic Alliance for Reform|UDAR]]'''\n|align=center bgcolor=#DE3163| 42\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''35'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 7\