#00B000| '''90'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 0\n|-----\n| '''[[Ukrainian Democratic Alliance for Reform|UDAR]]'''\n|align=center bgcolor=#DE3163| 42\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''42'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 0\n|-----\n| '''[[All-Ukrainian Union \"Svoboda\"|Svoboda]]'''\n|align=center bgcolor=#0095B6| 36\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''36'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 0\n|-----\n| '''[[Communist Party of Ukraine]]'''\n|align=center bgcolor=#FFAAAA| 31\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''0'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 31\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 0\n|-----\n| Not affiliated\n|align=center| 38\n|align=center bgcolor=#00B000| '''17'''\n|align=center bgcolor=red style=\"color:white;\"| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=yellow| 0\n|align=center bgcolor=purple style=\"color:white;\"| 4\n|align=center bgcolor=#cccccc| 17\n|+\n|}\n\n==Fall and temporary continuation as caretaker cabinet==\nAfter weeks of [[Euromaidan]] protests, and [[2014 Hrushevskoho Street riots|clashes, during which civilians were killed]]{{#tag:ref|The [[Ministry of Internal Affairs of Ukraine]] claimed on 25 January 2014 that a policeman who was walking home in civilian clothing had been killed by a shot in his head.<ref name=psdIU25114>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/187390.html Policeman shot dead in Kyiv, another policeman sustains knife wound - Ukrainian interior ministry], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (25 January 2014)</ref>|group=nb}}, Prime Minister Azarov offered his letter of resignation on 28 January 2014.<ref name=BBCNews2014a>{{cite news|title=Ukraine's PM Azarov and government resign|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-25932352|accessdate=28 January 2014|date=28 January 2014|author=BBC News}}</ref> According to his cabinet, Azarov was quoted saying that \"In order to create additional opportunities for socio-political compromise, for the sake of the peaceful settlement of the conflict, I have made a personal decision to ask the Ukrainian president to accept my resignation from the post of Ukrainian prime minister\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/187663.html|title=Ukrainian Prime Minister Azarov resigns|author=|date=|work=Interfax.com.ua|access-date=18 March 2017}}</ref> Under the [[Ukrainian constitution]] this meant the whole government had resigned.<ref name=EN28114AA/> The president subsequently accepted the resignation and signed a decree dismissing the cabinet, which decree would not take effect until the Verhovna Rada approved a new cabinet. Hence the second Azarov government continued as a caretaker government.<ref name=EN28114AA/> Prime Minister Azarov was replaced by deputy prime minister [[Serhiy Arbuzov]].<ref name=EN28114AA>[http://www.euronews.com/2014/01/28/ukrainian-parliament-votes-to-scrap-controversial-anti-protest-laws/ Ukrainian parliament delays vote on amnesty law until Wednesday], [[Euronews]] (28 January 2014)</ref> But under Ukrainian law the cabinet could be able to implement its duties for no more than 60 days.<ref name=60dcsag>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/188961.html Serhiy Arbuzov to head Ukraine govt pending premier's appointment], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (6 February 2014)</ref>\n\nThe [[February 2014 Euromaidan riots#Deal|compromise deal of February 21, 2014, between president Yanukovych and the opposition]] to end the [[February 2014 Euromaidan riots]] stipulated that a new [[national unity government]] was to be formed within ten days.<ref name=DTU21214>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/10655129/Ukraine-peace-hopes-in-the-air-as-president-loses-his-powers.html Ukraine: peace hopes in the air as president loses his powers], ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' (21 February 2014)</ref> On 27 February 2014 Ukraine's parliament approved a resolution to dismiss the government.<ref name=Afg27214/> They immediately followed it by the appointment of the new cabinet members of the [[First Yatsenyuk government|Yatsenyuk government]].<ref name=IU26214GNU>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/193035.html Maidan nominates Yatseniuk for prime minister], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (26 February 2014)<br />[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/193222.html Ukrainian parliament endorses new cabinet], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (27 February 2014)</ref>\n\n==Achievements==\nIn December 2013 the [[IMF]] stated that the Ukrainian government's policy mix had \"generated large external and fiscal imbalances\" and that this had \"contributed to deepening the recession in the country\".<ref>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/183061.html IMF slams Ukraine's macroeconomic policy], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (20 December 2013)</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n{{Azarov Government Two}}\n\n===Vice prime minister assignments===\n* First Vice PM \u2013 Serhiy Arbuzov\n** Ministry of Agrarian Policy and Food\n** Ministry of Economical Development and Trade\n** Ministry of Social Policy\n** Ministry of Finance\n** Ministry of Revenues and Duties\n* Vice PM \u2013 Yuri Boiko<ref name=Boiko/>\n** Ministry of Energy and Coal Industry\n** Ministry of Ecology and Natural Resources\n** Ministry of Industrial Policy\n**[[Space program of Ukraine|Space sector]]\n* Vice PM \u2013 Oleksandr Vilkul\n** Ministry of Infrastructure\n** Ministry of Regional Development, Construction and Housing\n* Vice PM \u2013 Kostyantyn Hryshchenko\n** Ministry of Culture\n** Ministry of Education and Science, Youth and Sport\n** Ministry of Health Security\n* Non-supervised ministries ([[National Security and Defense Council of Ukraine]])\n** Ministry of Justice\n** Ministry of Defense\n** Ministry of Foreign Affairs\n** Ministry of Internal Affairs\n** Ministry of Cabinet of Ministers\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|group=nb}}\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.kmu.gov.ua Governmental Portal of Ukraine] \u2013 official site of the Cabinet of Ministers\n\n{{Cabinets of Ukraine}}\n{{Politics of Ukraine footer}}\n{{Euromaidan}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Azarov, Mykola}}\n[[Category:Ukrainian governments]]\n[[Category:Cabinets established in 2012]]\n[[Category:2012 establishments in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:2014 disestablishments in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Cabinets disestablished in 2014]]\n[[Category:Euromaidan]]\n[[Category:7th Ukrainian Verkhovna Rada|Azarov]]\n", "name_user": "Quebec99", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix duplicate ref names \u2013You can help!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Second_Azarov_government"}
{"title_page": "Abatai", "text_new": "{{about|the Manchu prince|the village in [[Rennell Island]], [[Solomon Islands]]|Abatai, Rennell Island}}\n{{hatnote|This name uses [[Manchu name|Manchu naming customs]]. The family name is [[Aisin Gioro]].}}\n{{distinguish|Abahai (disambiguation)}}\n\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name  = Abatai\n| title = [[Prince An|Prince Raoyu of the Second Rank]]\n| image = \n| alt   = \n| caption = \n| succession  = [[Prince An|Prince Raoyu of the Second Rank]]\n| reign       = 1644\u20131646\n| predecessor = \n| successor   = \n| spouse      = Lady Nara\n| spouse-type = Consorts\n| issue       = \u0160anggiyan<br>Bohoto<br>[[Bolo, Prince Duanzhong|Bolo]], [[Prince Duanzhong|Prince Duanzhongding of the First Rank]]<br>Yolo, [[Prince An|Prince Anhe of the First Rank]]<br>Hedu\n| full name = Aisin Gioro Abatai<br>(\u611b\u65b0\u89ba\u7f85 \u963f\u5df4\u6cf0)\n| posthumous name = Prince Raoyumin of the Second Rank\n| house       = [[Aisin Gioro]]\n| father      = [[Nurhaci]]\n| mother      = Lady Irgen Gioro\n| birth_date  =  {{Birth date|1589|07|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  =  {{Death date and age|1646|05|10|1589|07|27|df=y}}\n| death_place = \n}}\n\n{{Chinese|c=\u963f\u5df4\u6cf0|p=\u0100b\u0101t\u00e0i|altname=Prince Raoyu|t2=\u9952\u9918\u90e1\u738b|s2=\u9976\u4f59\u90e1\u738b|p2=R\u00e1oy\u00f9 J\u00f9nw\u00e1ng}}\n\n'''Abatai''' ([[Manchu language|Manchu]]: [[File:abatai.png|14px]]; 27 July 1589 &ndash; 10 May 1646) was a [[Manchu people|Manchu]] prince and military general of the early [[Qing dynasty]]. Although an inconsistent and dissolute malcontent, he nevertheless showed considerable ability as a military leader and administrator.\n\n==Life==\nAbatai was born in the [[Manchu people|Manchu]] [[Aisin Gioro]] clan, the imperial clan of the [[Qing dynasty]], as part of the [[Plain Blue Banner]]. He was the seventh son of [[Nurhaci]], the [[Khan (title)|khan]] of the Later Jin dynasty, the precursor of the Qing dynasty. His mother, who was from the Irgen Gioro (\u4f0a\u723e\u6839\u89ba\u7f85) clan, was a concubine of Nurhaci.\n\nAbatai led Later Jin forces to attack the tribes of Weji in 1611 and those of [[Jarut]] in 1623. He was disciplined for abandoning his colleagues during a raid on territories of the [[Ming dynasty|Ming Empire]] in 1629. He was also held responsible for the loss of Yongping and other conquered Ming cities in 1629 and 1630.\n\nIn 1631, Abatai was appointed to the Manchu Board of Works. He was reprimanded for incompetence at the siege of [[Dalian]] in 1633 but reformed his conduct, and with his younger half-brother [[Ajige]], he reputedly fought and won 56 engagements. He was handsomely rewarded in 1636 for his achievements in battle.\n\nIn 1641, Abatai was stripped of his ranks for withdrawing without permission during the siege of [[Jinzhou]] in 1641. He then led a raiding force into northern China, advancing into [[Zhili]], [[Shandong]] and [[Jiangsu]] from 1642 to 1643.\n\nIn 1644, Abatai was granted the title \"[[Prince An|Prince Raoyu of the Second Rank]]\" (\u9952\u9918\u90e1\u738b), and in the following year he was placed in command of the military in Shandong. He died in 1646.\n\n==Family==\n* Father: [[Nurhaci]], Taizu ({{lang|zh|\u592a\u7956 \u52aa\u723e\u54c8\u8d64}}; 8 April 1559 \u2013 30 September 1626)\n** Grandfather: [[Taksi]], Xianzu ({{lang|zh|\u986f\u7956 \u5854\u514b\u4e16}}; 1543\u20131583)\n** Grandmother: Empress Xuan, of the [[Hitara]] clan ({{lang|zh|\u5ba3\u7687\u540e \u559c\u5854\u81d8\u6c0f}}; d. 1569), personal name Emeci ({{lang|zh|\u984d\u7a46\u9f4a}})\n* Mother: Secondary consort, of the [[Irgen Gioro]] clan ({{lang|zh|\u5074\u798f\u6649 \u4f0a\u723e\u6839\u89ba\u7f85\u6c0f}})\n----\n* Consorts and Issue:\n** Primary consort, of the [[Clan Nara#Notable figures of the Nara|Nara]] clan ({{lang|zh|\u5ae1\u798f\u6649 \u90a3\u62c9\u6c0f}})\n*** \u0160anggiyan, Prince Xianque of the Fourth Rank ({{lang|zh|\u8ce2\u6128\u8c9d\u5b50 \u5c1a\u5efa}}; 1606\u20131630), first son\n*** Bohoto, Prince Wenliang of the Fourth Rank ({{lang|zh|\u6eab\u826f\u8c9d\u5b50 \u535a\u548c\u8bac}}; 1610 \u2013 October/November 1648), second son\n*** [[Bolo, Prince Duanzhong|Bolo]], [[Prince Duanzhong|Prince Duanzhongding of the First Rank]] ({{lang|zh|\u7aef\u91cd\u5b9a\u89aa\u738b \u535a\u6d1b}}; 1613 \u2013 23 April 1652), third son\n*** Yolo, [[Prince An|Prince Anhe of the First Rank]] ({{lang|zh|\u5b89\u548c\u89aa\u738b \u5cb3\u6a02}}; 19 October 1625 \u2013 15 March 1689), fourth son\n*** Hedu ({{lang|zh|\u548c\u5ea6}}), fifth son\n*** First daughter\n**** Married [[Li Yongfang]] ({{lang|zh|\u674e\u6c38\u82b3}}; d. 1634) in 1618\n*** Second daughter\n**** Married Ingg\u016bldai ({{lang|zh|\u82f1\u4fc4\u723e\u5cb1}}; 1596\u20131648) of the Manchu [[Tatara (clan)|Tatara]] clan\n** Unknown\n*** A daughter who married Chuo'erji ({{lang|zh|\u7dbd\u723e\u6fdf}}; d. 1670) of the [[Borjigin#Khorchin Mongols|Khorchin Borjigit]] clan, and had issue ([[Empress Xiaohuizhang]])\n*** A daughter who married Bu'erhatu ({{lang|zh|\u5e03\u723e\u54c8\u5716}})\n\n==See also==\n* [[Royal and noble ranks of the Qing dynasty]]\n* [[Ranks of Imperial Consorts in China#Qing]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{cite book|last=Du|first=Jiaji|title=Baqi Yu Qingchao Zhengzhi Lun Gao (Draft on the Eight Banners and Politics of the Qing Dynasty)|year=2008|publisher=People's Publishing House|ref=harv|isbn=9787010067537}}\n* {{cite book|last=Hummel|first=Arthur W.|authorlink=Arthur W. Hummel, Sr.|title=[[Eminent Chinese of the Ch'ing Period]]|year=1943|publisher=[[United States Government Printing Office]]|ref=harv|isbn=}}\n* {{cite book|last=Zhao|first=Erxun|authorlink=Zhao Erxun|volume=162, 217|title=[[Draft History of Qing]] (Qing Shi Gao)|year=1928|ref=harv|isbn=}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Abatai}}\n[[Category:1589 births]]\n[[Category:1646 deaths]]\n[[Category:Manchu politicians]]\n[[Category:Nurhaci's sons]]\n[[Category:House of Aisin Gioro]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the Manchu prince|the village in [[Rennell Island]], [[Solomon Islands]]|Abatai, Rennell Island}}\n{{hatnote|This name uses [[Manchu name|Manchu naming customs]]. The family name is [[Aisin Gioro]].}}\n{{distinguish|Abahai (disambiguation)}}\n\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name  = Abatai\n| title = [[Prince An|Prince Raoyu of the Second Rank]]\n| image = \n| alt   = \n| caption = \n| succession  = [[Prince An|Prince Raoyu of the Second Rank]]\n| reign       = 1644\u20131646\n| predecessor = \n| successor   = \n| spouse      = Lady Nara\n| spouse-type = Consorts\n| issue       = \u0160anggiyan<br>Bohoto<br>[[Bolo, Prince Duanzhong|Bolo]], [[Prince Duanzhong|Prince Duanzhongding of the First Rank]]<br>Yolo, [[Prince An|Prince Anhe of the First Rank]]<br>Hedu\n| full name = Aisin Gioro Abatai<br>(\u611b\u65b0\u89ba\u7f85 \u963f\u5df4\u6cf0)\n| posthumous name = Prince Raoyumin of the Second Rank\n| house       = [[Aisin Gioro]]\n| father      = [[Nurhaci]]\n| mother      = Lady Irgen Gioro\n| birth_date  =  {{Birth date|1589|07|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  =  {{Death date and age|1646|05|10|1589|07|27|df=y}}\n| death_place = \n}}\n\n{{Chinese|c=\u963f\u5df4\u6cf0|p=\u0100b\u0101t\u00e0i|altname=Prince Raoyu|t2=\u9952\u9918\u90e1\u738b|s2=\u9976\u4f59\u90e1\u738b|p2=R\u00e1oy\u00f9 J\u00f9nw\u00e1ng}}\n\n'''Abatai''' ([[Manchu language|Manchu]]: [[File:abatai.png|14px]]; 27 July 1589 &ndash; 10 May 1646) was a [[Manchu people|Manchu]] prince and military general of the early [[Qing dynasty]]. Although an inconsistent and dissolute malcontent, he nevertheless showed considerable ability as a military leader and administrator.\n\n==Life==\nAbatai was born in the [[Manchu people|Manchu]] [[Aisin Gioro]] clan, the imperial clan of the [[Qing dynasty]], as part of the [[Plain Blue Banner]]. He was the seventh son of [[Nurhaci]], the [[Khan (title)|khan]] of the Later Jin dynasty, the precursor of the Qing dynasty. His mother, who was from the Irgen Gioro (\u4f0a\u723e\u6839\u89ba\u7f85) clan, was a concubine of Nurhaci.\n\nAbatai led Later Jin forces to attack the tribes of Weji in 1611 and those of [[Jarut]] in 1623. He was disciplined for abandoning his colleagues during a raid on territories of the [[Ming dynasty|Ming Empire]] in 1629. He was also held responsible for the loss of Yongping and other conquered Ming cities in 1629 and 1630.\n\nIn 1631, Abatai was appointed to the Manchu Board of Works. He was reprimanded for incompetence at the siege of [[Dalian]] in 1633 but reformed his conduct, and with his younger half-brother [[Ajige]], he reputedly fought and won 56 engagements. He was handsomely rewarded in 1636 for his achievements in battle.\n\nIn 1641, Abatai was stripped off his ranks for withdrawing without permission during the siege of [[Jinzhou]] in 1641. He then led a raiding force into northern China, advancing into [[Zhili]], [[Shandong]] and [[Jiangsu]] from 1642 to 1643.\n\nIn 1644, Abatai was granted the title \"[[Prince An|Prince Raoyu of the Second Rank]]\" (\u9952\u9918\u90e1\u738b), and in the following year he was placed in command of the military in Shandong. He died in 1646.\n\n==Family==\n* Father: [[Nurhaci]], Taizu ({{lang|zh|\u592a\u7956 \u52aa\u723e\u54c8\u8d64}}; 8 April 1559 \u2013 30 September 1626)\n** Grandfather: [[Taksi]], Xianzu ({{lang|zh|\u986f\u7956 \u5854\u514b\u4e16}}; 1543\u20131583)\n** Grandmother: Empress Xuan, of the [[Hitara]] clan ({{lang|zh|\u5ba3\u7687\u540e \u559c\u5854\u81d8\u6c0f}}; d. 1569), personal name Emeci ({{lang|zh|\u984d\u7a46\u9f4a}})\n* Mother: Secondary consort, of the [[Irgen Gioro]] clan ({{lang|zh|\u5074\u798f\u6649 \u4f0a\u723e\u6839\u89ba\u7f85\u6c0f}})\n----\n* Consorts and Issue:\n** Primary consort, of the [[Clan Nara#Notable figures of the Nara|Nara]] clan ({{lang|zh|\u5ae1\u798f\u6649 \u90a3\u62c9\u6c0f}})\n*** \u0160anggiyan, Prince Xianque of the Fourth Rank ({{lang|zh|\u8ce2\u6128\u8c9d\u5b50 \u5c1a\u5efa}}; 1606\u20131630), first son\n*** Bohoto, Prince Wenliang of the Fourth Rank ({{lang|zh|\u6eab\u826f\u8c9d\u5b50 \u535a\u548c\u8bac}}; 1610 \u2013 October/November 1648), second son\n*** [[Bolo, Prince Duanzhong|Bolo]], [[Prince Duanzhong|Prince Duanzhongding of the First Rank]] ({{lang|zh|\u7aef\u91cd\u5b9a\u89aa\u738b \u535a\u6d1b}}; 1613 \u2013 23 April 1652), third son\n*** Yolo, [[Prince An|Prince Anhe of the First Rank]] ({{lang|zh|\u5b89\u548c\u89aa\u738b \u5cb3\u6a02}}; 19 October 1625 \u2013 15 March 1689), fourth son\n*** Hedu ({{lang|zh|\u548c\u5ea6}}), fifth son\n*** First daughter\n**** Married [[Li Yongfang]] ({{lang|zh|\u674e\u6c38\u82b3}}; d. 1634) in 1618\n*** Second daughter\n**** Married Ingg\u016bldai ({{lang|zh|\u82f1\u4fc4\u723e\u5cb1}}; 1596\u20131648) of the Manchu [[Tatara (clan)|Tatara]] clan\n** Unknown\n*** A daughter who married Chuo'erji ({{lang|zh|\u7dbd\u723e\u6fdf}}; d. 1670) of the [[Borjigin#Khorchin Mongols|Khorchin Borjigit]] clan, and had issue ([[Empress Xiaohuizhang]])\n*** A daughter who married Bu'erhatu ({{lang|zh|\u5e03\u723e\u54c8\u5716}})\n\n==See also==\n* [[Royal and noble ranks of the Qing dynasty]]\n* [[Ranks of Imperial Consorts in China#Qing]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{cite book|last=Du|first=Jiaji|title=Baqi Yu Qingchao Zhengzhi Lun Gao (Draft on the Eight Banners and Politics of the Qing Dynasty)|year=2008|publisher=People's Publishing House|ref=harv|isbn=9787010067537}}\n* {{cite book|last=Hummel|first=Arthur W.|authorlink=Arthur W. Hummel, Sr.|title=[[Eminent Chinese of the Ch'ing Period]]|year=1943|publisher=[[United States Government Printing Office]]|ref=harv|isbn=}}\n* {{cite book|last=Zhao|first=Erxun|authorlink=Zhao Erxun|volume=162, 217|title=[[Draft History of Qing]] (Qing Shi Gao)|year=1928|ref=harv|isbn=}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Abatai}}\n[[Category:1589 births]]\n[[Category:1646 deaths]]\n[[Category:Manchu politicians]]\n[[Category:Nurhaci's sons]]\n[[Category:House of Aisin Gioro]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife:Typo fixing, replaced: stripped off \u2192 stripped of", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abatai"}
{"title_page": "Jonathan Nez", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Jonathan Nez\n| image = Jonathan Nez - 2020.jpg\n|caption = Jonathan Nez in 2020\n| office = 9th [[President of the Navajo Nation]]\n| vicepresident = [[Myron Lizer]]\n| term_start = January 15, 2019\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Russell Begaye]]\n| successor = \n| office1 = 8th [[Vice President of the Navajo Nation]]\n| president1 = [[Russell Begaye]]\n| term_start1 = May 12, 2015\n| term_end1 = January 15, 2019\n| predecessor1 = [[Rex Lee Jim]]\n| successor1 = [[Myron Lizer]]\n| birth_date = {{birth based on age as of date|43|2018|11|8}}<ref>[https://www.navajotimes.com/reznews/nez-youngest-ever/ Nez: Youngest ever]</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Tuba City, Arizona|Tuba City]], [[Arizona]], U.S.\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| spouse = Phefelia Herbert\n| education = [[Northland Pioneer College]]<br>[[Northern Arizona University]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]], [[Master of Public Administration|MPA]])\n}}\n'''Jonathan Nez''' (born May 26, 1975<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/NezLizer2018/posts/2223500467915484|title=Navajo Nation President Jonathan Nez and Vice President Myron Lizer|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://navajotimes.com/reznews/nez-youngest-ever/|title=Nez: Youngest ever|last=Council|first=About The Author <img src=\"https://navajotimes com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/arlyssa-becenti-mug-web-440x440 jpg\" width=\"170\" height=\"170\" alt=\"Arlyssa Becenti\" class=\"avatar avatar-170 wp-user-avatar wp-user-avatar-170 alignnone photo\" /> Arlyssa Becenti Arlyssa Becenti reports on Navajo Nation|last2=Business|date=2018-11-08|website=Navajo Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09|last3=Agency|first3=Fort Defiance|last4=politics|first4=New Mexico State|last5=T\u00e1chii'nii|first5=Art/fashion Her clans are N\u00e1t'oh dine'\u00e9|last6=Bit'ahnii|last7=\u0142ichii'nii|first7=Kin|last8=Defiance|first8=Kiyaa'\u00e1anii She\u2019s originally from Fort}}</ref>) is the 9th and current president of the [[Navajo Nation]]. He was elected [[President of the Navajo Nation]] on [[Navajo Nation presidential election, 2018|November 6, 2018]].<ref name=\"ABQJournal_2018-11-07_generalresults\" /> Before his election, Nez served as Vice President from 2015 until his inauguration in early January 2019.<ref name=\"USHR_2017_nezbio\" /> At 43 years of age, Nez is the youngest person to have ever been elected President of the Navajo Nation.<ref name=\"navajotimes_20181107_nezwin\" />\n\n== Life and career ==\nNez was born in [[Tuba City, Arizona|Tuba City]], [[Arizona]], and attended [[Northland Pioneer College]] and [[Northern Arizona University]].<ref name=\"USHR_2017_nezbio\" /> He attained both a [[Bachelor of Science|BS]] in [[Political science]] and a [[Master of Public Administration|Masters of Public Administration]] from NAU.<ref name=\"USHR_2017_nezbio\" />\n\nBefore being elected Vice President of the Navajo Nation, Nez served as vice president of the Shonto chapter, delegate to the [[Navajo Nation Council]] representing the [[Oljato\u2013Monument Valley, Utah|Oljato]], Ts'ah Bii' Kin, [[Navajo Mountain (Chapter)|Navajo Mountain]], and [[Shonto, Arizona|Shonto]] chapters.<ref name=\"USHR_2017_nezbio\" /> He was sworn in to the office of Vice President of the Navajo Nation on May 12, 2015,<ref name=\"navajotimes_20150512_inauguration\" /> and sworn in to office of President on January 15, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/c67321942211477294a63ca4bf16f752|title=The Latest: Jonathan Nez sworn in as Navajo Nation president|date=2019-01-15|website=AP NEWS|access-date=2019-02-03}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"USHR_2017_nezbio\">{{cite web\n| url           = https://docs.house.gov/meetings/AP/AP06/20170516/105949/HHRG-115-AP06-Bio-NezJ-20170516.pdf\n| title         = Navajo Nation Vice President Jonathan M. Nez\n| website       = United States House of Representatives\n| access-date   = 2018-11-09\n| archive-url   = https://web.archive.org/web/20170519062553/https://docs.house.gov/meetings/AP/AP06/20170516/105949/HHRG-115-AP06-Bio-NezJ-20170516.pdf\n| archive-date  = 2017-05-19\n| url-status      = live\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"navajotimes_20150512_inauguration\">{{cite news\n| last          = Donovan\n| first         = Bill\n| url           = https://www.navajotimes.com/rezpolitics/a-number-of-firsts-at-navajo-presidential-inauguration/\n| title         = A number of firsts at Navajo presidential inauguration\n| date          = 2015-05-12\n| access-date   = 2018-11-09\n| work          = [[The Navajo Times]]\n| archive-url   = https://web.archive.org/web/20150517070921/https://www.navajotimes.com/rezpolitics/a-number-of-firsts-at-navajo-presidential-inauguration/\n| archive-date  = 2015-05-17\n| url-status      = live\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ABQJournal_2018-11-07_generalresults\">{{cite news\n| last          = Smith\n| first         = Noel Lyn\n| title         = Voters on the Navajo Nation elect president, council delegates\n| url           = https://www.daily-times.com/story/news/politics/elections/2018/11/08/midterm-elections-2018-navajo-nation-new-mexico-results/1921939002/\n| work          = [[Farmington Daily Times]]\n| date          = 2018-11-08\n| access-date   = 2018-11-09\n| archive-url   = https://web.archive.org/web/20181108211639/https://www.daily-times.com/story/news/politics/elections/2018/11/08/midterm-elections-2018-navajo-nation-new-mexico-results/1921939002/?from=new-cookie\n| archive-date  = 2018-11-08\n| url-status      = live\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"navajotimes_20181107_nezwin\">{{cite news\n| last          = Becenti\n| first         = Arlyssa\n| title         = Nez wins by 19,000 votes\n| url           = https://www.navajotimes.com/reznews/nez-wins-by-19000-votes/\n| work          = [[The Navajo Times]]\n| date          = 2018-11-07\n| access-date   = 2018-11-10\n| archive-url   = https://web.archive.org/web/20181107230224/https://www.navajotimes.com/reznews/nez-wins-by-19000-votes/\n| archive-date  = 2018-11-07\n| url-status      = live\n}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons cat}}\n* [http://www.opvp.navajo-nsn.gov/About-Us/President-Jonathan-Nez Navajo Nation Office of the President and Vice President]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Russell Begaye]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of the Navajo Nation]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Presidents of the Navajo Nation}}\n{{Vice Presidents of the Navajo Nation}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nez, Jonathan}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Native American politicians]]\n[[Category:Northern Arizona University alumni]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Navajo Nation]]\n[[Category:Vice Presidents of the Navajo Nation]]\n[[Category:Arizona Democrats]]\n[[Category:People from Tuba City, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Jonathan Nez\n| image = Jonathan Nez - 2020.jpg\n|caption = Jonathan Nez in 2020\n| office = 9th [[President of the Navajo Nation]]\n| vicepresident = [[Myron Lizer]]\n| term_start = January 15, 2019\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Russell Begaye]]\n| successor = \n| office1 = 8th [[Vice President of the Navajo Nation]]\n| president1 = [[Russell Begaye]]\n| term_start1 = May 12, 2015\n| term_end1 = January 15, 2019\n| predecessor1 = [[Rex Lee Jim]]\n| successor1 = [[Myron Lizer]]\n| birth_date = {{birth based on age as of date|43|2018|11|8}}<ref>[https://www.navajotimes.com/reznews/nez-youngest-ever/ Nez: Youngest ever]</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Tuba City, Arizona|Tuba City]], [[Arizona]], U.S.\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| spouse = Phefelia Herbert\n| education = [[Northland Pioneer College]]<br>[[Northern Arizona University]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]], [[Master of Public Administration|MPA]])\n}}\n'''Jonathan Nez''' (born May 26, 1975<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/NezLizer2018/posts/2223500467915484|title=Navajo Nation President Jonathan Nez and Vice President Myron Lizer|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>) is the 9th and current president of the [[Navajo Nation]]. He was elected [[President of the Navajo Nation]] on [[Navajo Nation presidential election, 2018|November 6, 2018]].<ref name=\"ABQJournal_2018-11-07_generalresults\" /> Before his election, Nez served as Vice President from 2015 until his inauguration in early January 2019.<ref name=\"USHR_2017_nezbio\" /> At 43 years of age, Nez is the youngest person to have ever been elected President of the Navajo Nation.<ref name=\"navajotimes_20181107_nezwin\" />\n\n== Life and career ==\nNez was born in [[Tuba City, Arizona|Tuba City]], [[Arizona]], and attended [[Northland Pioneer College]] and [[Northern Arizona University]].<ref name=\"USHR_2017_nezbio\" /> He attained both a [[Bachelor of Science|BS]] in [[Political science]] and a [[Master of Public Administration|Masters of Public Administration]] from NAU.<ref name=\"USHR_2017_nezbio\" />\n\nBefore being elected Vice President of the Navajo Nation, Nez served as vice president of the Shonto chapter, delegate to the [[Navajo Nation Council]] representing the [[Oljato\u2013Monument Valley, Utah|Oljato]], Ts'ah Bii' Kin, [[Navajo Mountain (Chapter)|Navajo Mountain]], and [[Shonto, Arizona|Shonto]] chapters.<ref name=\"USHR_2017_nezbio\" /> He was sworn in to the office of Vice President of the Navajo Nation on May 12, 2015,<ref name=\"navajotimes_20150512_inauguration\" /> and sworn in to office of President on January 15, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/c67321942211477294a63ca4bf16f752|title=The Latest: Jonathan Nez sworn in as Navajo Nation president|date=2019-01-15|website=AP NEWS|access-date=2019-02-03}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|re